\begin_layout Subsection
线性双曲型方程组
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Find 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 smooth functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ U_{i}(x,t)\right\} _{i=1}^{m}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the system of PDEs
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{U_{i}}{t}+\sum_{k=1}^{m}A_{ik}\pdv{U_{k}}{x}=0\qquad(x,t)\in(-\infty,\infty)\times(t_{0},\infty)\qquad i=1,\dots,m
\]

\end_inset

and the system of smooth ICs
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{i}(x_{0},t_{0})=U_{i}^{0}(x_{0})\qquad i=1,\dots,m
\]

\end_inset

in which, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ik}$
\end_inset

 are constants, and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the matrix notation just introduced, the problem can be rewritten
 in a more compact form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prob:LinearPdeSystemWithSmoothIC"

\end_inset

Find a column matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 smooth functions, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U(x,t)}$
\end_inset

, satisfying the PDE
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\pdv{t}+\Matrix{A}\pdv{x}\right)\ket{U}=\ket{0}\qquad(x,t)\in(-\infty,\infty)\times(t_{0},\infty)\label{eq:LinearPdeSystem1d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the smooth IC
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ket{U(x_{0},t_{0})}=\ket{U^{0}(x_{0})}\qquad x_{0}\in(-\infty,\infty)\label{eq:SmoothInitialWaveSystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Given a square matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

.
 If a scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, a row matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra{L}$
\end_inset

 and a column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{R}$
\end_inset

 together satisfy the following equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bra{L}\Matrix{A}=\bra{L}\lambda\qquad\Matrix{A}\ket{R}=\lambda\ket{R}
\]

\end_inset

then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an 
\noun on
eigenvalue
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
eigen!~value
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra{L}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\noun on
left eigenvector
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
eigen!~vector!left ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\noun on
right eigenvector
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
eigen!~vector!right ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[Hyperbolic PDE System]
\end_layout

\end_inset

If all of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

 in PDE 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LinearPdeSystem1d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are real numbers, and there are 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 linearly independent (left/right) eigenvectors, then the PDE system is
 said to be 
\noun on
hyperbolic
\noun default
.
 Moreover, if all of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 real eigenvalues are distinct, then the system is said to be 
\noun on
strictly hyperbolic
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From now on, we shall assume the systems to be studied are strictly hyperbolic,
 and all of their eigenvalues have been sorted, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{1}<\cdots<\lambda_{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
If PDE 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LinearPdeSystem1d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is strictly hyperbolic, then it can be decomposed as 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 independent linear wave equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The eigenvectors corresponding to distinct eigenvalues are linearly independent
 with each other.
 We can collect them into matrices, which will be informally called 
\noun on
eigenmatrices
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
eigen!~matrix
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Matrix{R}:=\begin{bmatrix}\ket{R_{1}} & \cdots & \ket{R_{m}}\end{bmatrix}\qquad\Matrix{L}:=\begin{bmatrix}\bra{L_{1}}\\
\vdots\\
\bra{L_{m}}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

They are both invertible, since their columns and rows are linear independent.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

 can be diagonalized:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Matrix{A}\Matrix{R}=\Matrix{R}\Matrix{\lambda}\implies\Matrix{A}=\Matrix{R}\Matrix{\lambda}\Matrix{R}^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Matrix{L}\Matrix{A}=\Matrix{\lambda}\Matrix{L}\implies\Matrix{A}=\Matrix{L}^{-1}\Matrix{\lambda}\Matrix{L}
\]

\end_inset

The right and left eigenmatrices can be calculated independently.
 However, we note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Matrix{A}=\Matrix{R}\Matrix{\lambda}\Matrix{R}^{-1}\implies\Matrix{R}^{-1}\Matrix{A}=\Matrix{\lambda}\Matrix{R}^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{R}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{L}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Matrix{L}:=\Matrix{R}^{-1}\qquad\ip{L_{i}}{R_{k}}=\begin{cases}
1 & i=k\\
0 & i\ne k
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

We shall use such 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{L}$
\end_inset

 from now on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By defining a set of 
\noun on
characteristic variables
\noun default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{V(x,t)}:=\Matrix{L}\ket{U(x,t)}=\begin{bmatrix}\ip{L_{1}}{U(x,t)}\\
\vdots\\
\ip{L_{m}}{U(x,t)}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}V_{1}(x,t)\\
\vdots\\
V_{m}(x,t)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

the original system can be decoupled as 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 independent linear wave equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\pdv{t}+\Matrix{\lambda}\pdv{x}\right)\ket{V}=\ket{0}\qor\pdv{V_{i}}{t}+\lambda_{i}\pdv{V_{i}}{x}\qquad i=1,\dots,m
\]

\end_inset

which is called the 
\noun on
characteristic form
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
characteristic!~ form
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ofPDE 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LinearPdeSystem1d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The solution of IVP 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "prob:LinearPdeSystemWithSmoothIC"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\ket{U(x,t)}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}\ket{R_{i}}\ip{L_{i}}{U^{0}(x-(t-t_{0})\lambda_{i})}}\qquad(x,t)\in(-\infty,\infty)\times[t_{0},\infty)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 linear wave equations is supplied with an IC obtained from the same projection:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{V^{0}(x_{0})}:=\Matrix{L}\ket{U^{0}(x_{0})}=\begin{bmatrix}\ip{L_{1}}{U^{0}(x_{0})}\\
\vdots\\
\ip{L_{m}}{U^{0}(x_{0})}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

and can be solved along the corresponding characteristic curve:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{x-x_{0}}{t-t_{0}}=\lambda_{i}\impliedby\begin{cases}
\dv*{x}{t}=\lambda_{i} & t\in(t_{0},\infty)\\
x(0)=x_{0}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

which is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{i}(x,t)=\ip{L_{i}}{U^{0}(x-(t-t_{0})\lambda_{i})}
\]

\end_inset

This is a single wave with the shape 
\begin_inset Formula $\ip{L_{i}}{U^{0}(x_{0})}$
\end_inset

 propagating with the speed 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The solution to the original system can be obtained by transforming 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{V}$
\end_inset

 back into 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\ket{U(x,t)} & =\Matrix{L}^{-1}\ket{V(x,t)}=\Matrix{R}\ket{V(x,t)}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}\ket{R_{1}} & \cdots & \ket{R_{m}}\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}V_{1}(x,t)\\
\vdots\\
V_{m}(x,t)
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{m}\ket{R_{i}}\ip{L_{i}}{U^{0}(x-(t-t_{0})\lambda_{i})}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
拟线性双曲型方程组
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:QuasilinearHyperbolicSystems"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Find 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 smooth functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ U_{i}(x,t)\right\} _{i=1}^{m}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the PDE system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\pdv{t}+\Matrix{A(U)}\pdv{x}\right)\ket{U}=\ket{0}\label{eq:QuasilinearHyperbolicSystem1d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the smooth IC system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SmoothInitialWaveSystem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A(U)}$
\end_inset

 is a matrix function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like a linear system, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A(U)}$
\end_inset

 can be diagonalized at any arbitrary point 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\dots,U_{m})$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\Matrix{A(U)} & =\Matrix{R(U)}\Matrix{\lambda(U)}\Matrix{R(U)}^{-1}\\
 & =\Matrix{L(U)}^{-1}\Matrix{\lambda(U)}\Matrix{L(U)}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

However, PDE system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QuasilinearHyperbolicSystem1d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 cannot be fully decoupled in general.
 We can at most have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\Matrix{L(U)}\pdv{t}+\Matrix{\lambda(U)}\Matrix{L(U)}\pdv{x}\right)\ket{U}=\ket{0}
\]

\end_inset

each row of which is a 
\noun on
characteristic compatibility condition
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
characteristic!~ compatibility condition
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which can be written as a PDE
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mel**{L_{i}(U)}{\pdv{t}+\lambda_{i}(U)\pdv{x}}{U}=0\qquad i=1,\dots,m\label{eq:CharacteristicCompatibilityCondition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or an ODE
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ip{L_{i}(U)}{\left(\dv{t}\right)_{i}{U}}=0\qquad i=1,\dots,m
\]

\end_inset

by defining a differential operator
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\dv{t}\right)_{i}:=\pdv{t}+\lambda_{i}(U)\pdv{x}
\]

\end_inset

along the characteristic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv*{x}{t}=\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In contrast to the linear case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra{L_{i}(U)}$
\end_inset

 cannot be exchanged with the differential operator, so the characteristic
 compatibility condition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:CharacteristicCompatibilityCondition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 cannot be decoupled into 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 independent PDEs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(U_{1},\dots,U_{m})$
\end_inset

 defines a scalar field in the 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-space, which is called the 
\noun on

\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th characteristic field
\noun default
.
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
characteristic!~ field
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A characteristic field is categorized as 
\noun on
genuinely nonlinear
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
characteristic!~ field!genuinely nonlinear ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ip{\grad\lambda_{i}}{R_{i}}\ne0\qquad\forall(U_{1},\cdots,U_{m})\in\Omega\subset(-\infty,\infty)^{m}
\]

\end_inset

or 
\noun on
linearly degenerate
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
characteristic!~ field!linearly degenerate ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ip{\grad\lambda_{i}}{R_{i}}=0\qquad\forall(U_{1},\cdots,U_{m})\in\Omega\subset(-\infty,\infty)^{m}
\]

\end_inset

in which
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bra{\grad\lambda_{i}}:=\begin{bmatrix}\pdv{\lambda_{i}}{U_{1}} & \cdots & \pdv{\lambda_{i}}{U_{m}}\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Riemann 不变量
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
广义与狭义 Riemann 不变量
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A remedy for the difficulty mentioned above, proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Riemann"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernhard_Riemann"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, is to find 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 independent numbers that might turn the PDE system into a system of 
\emph on
algebraic
\emph default
 equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[Riemann Invariants]
\end_layout

\end_inset

If a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U_{1},\cdots,U_{m})$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ip{\grad{\phi}}{R_{k}}=0\qquad\forall(U_{1},\cdots,U_{m})\in\Omega\subset(-\infty,\infty)^{m}
\]

\end_inset

then it is called a
\noun on
 generalized 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-Riemann invariant
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Riemann!~ invariant!generalized ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
If a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(U_{1},\cdots,U_{m})$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bra{\grad{\psi}}\parallel\bra{L_{k}}=0\qquad\forall(U_{1},\cdots,U_{m})\in\Omega\subset(-\infty,\infty)^{m}
\]

\end_inset

then it is called a
\noun on
 specialized 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-Riemann invariant
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Riemann!~ invariant!specialized ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
A generalized 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-Riemann invariant 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is constant along the trajectory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{R_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\ip{\grad{\phi}}{R_{k}}$
\end_inset

 is the directional derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{R_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 So, along 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\dd{U}}=\ket{R_{k}}\dd{\xi}$
\end_inset

, which is an infinitesimal segment along the trajectory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{R_{k}}$
\end_inset

, there is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dd{\phi}=\ip{\grad{\phi}}{\dd{U}}=\ip{\grad{\phi}}{R_{k}}\dd{\xi}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $(m-1)$
\end_inset

 independent generalized 
\noun on

\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-
\noun default
Riemann invariants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The constancy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k}$
\end_inset

 (the trajectory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{R_{k}}$
\end_inset

) leads to an algebraic equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(U_{1},\dots,U_{m}\right)=C
\]

\end_inset

which defines a hyper-surface in the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U_{1},\dots,U_{m}\right)$
\end_inset

 space.
 The intersection of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such hyper-surfaces is an 
\begin_inset Formula $(m-n)$
\end_inset

-manifold.
 The intersection of all such hyper-surfaces is 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k}$
\end_inset

, which is a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-manifold, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n=m-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

